description.plain:
Ibeyi are French-Cuban twins, Naomi and Lisa-Kaindé Diaz. They grew up in Paris and are daughters of late Cuban percussionist Angá Diaz, who played with Buena Vista Social Club.

Naomi plays percussive instruments, the Cajon and the Batas, whilst Lisa plays piano. Together the sisters have learned the songs of their father’s culture, Yoruba. Lisa is the songwriter of the group.

Yoruba travelled from West Africa to Cuba with slavery in the 1700s. The Yoruba people have the highest twinning rate in the world, and twins occupy an important position within Yoruba culture. Ibeyi is pronounced “ee-bey-ee,” and means “twins” in Yoruba.

Ibeyi sing in English, French, Yoruba and Spanish, and have created a minimalist sound that merges elements of their heritage with their natural love for modern music. They cite artists such as Frank Ocean, James Blake, and King Krule amongst their wide range of influences. Their music fuses jazz with beats, samples with traditional instruments.

At the age of 20, they released their debut self-titled album. The album pays tribute to their deceased father and the track “Yanira” immortalizes the duo’s older sister, who died in 2013. In 2014, they received attention for the video for their album’s second single, “River.” The twin sisters appear in a close-up shot throughout, taking turns having their heads forced underwater while the other sings.

In 2015, the sisters were endorsed by Beyoncé, and the following year they took part in Bey’s Lemonade.

songs.title: River

description.plain:
This song, written by the French-Cuban twin sisters, Ibeyi (pronounced ee-bey-ee. And ‘Ibeji’ means ‘Twins’ in Yoruba), is dedicated to the Yoruba goddess of sweet, fresh waters. She is widely loved and known for healing the sick and bringing fertility and prosperity, and She especially watches over the poor and brings them what they need. As Orisha of love, Oshun is represented as a beautiful, charming and coquettish young woman. In some tales She is said to be a mermaid with a fish tail.

songs.title: Mama Says

description.plain:
This song is about the loss of Lisa-Kaindé and Naomi’s father and how their mother is dealing with that loss.

Towards the end of the song, they sing a song to Elegua and the lyrics “the man is gone, there is no life without him” refer to Elegua, the yoruban orisha of communication. He is the bridge between the spiritual world and the material world. He is the first orisha to be saluted in any ceremony.

songs.title: Deathless

description.plain:
“Deathless” is a single by Ibeyi, released on August 31, 2017.

The song features supporting sax contribution from Kamasi Washington.

“Deathless” was written by Lisa-Kaindé Diaz and is inspired by her wrongful, racially-motivated arrest at 16 in Paris. The incident resurfaced during a conversation about police brutality with Richard Russell, head of their label XL Recordings and producer of both their albums, who encouraged Lisa to write a song about her experience.

songs.full_title: No Man Is Big Enough For My Arms by Ibeyi
songs.title: No Man Is Big Enough For My Arms
songs.title_with_featured: No Man Is Big Enough For My Arms

description.plain:
The title is taken from an excerpt in Jennifer Clement’s biography Widow Basquiat: A Memoir, which documents the relationship between Jean-Michel Basquiat and his lover Suzanne Mallouk. The book was given to Lisa-Kaindé Diaz by Richard Russell during the making of Ash and in it, Mallouk remembers telling an older man, “No man is big enough for my arms” when she was seven-years-old.

The track merges excerpts from Michelle Obama’s New Hampshire speech in October 2016, calling out Donald Trump and his treatment of women.

songs.title: Think of You

description.plain:
“Think Of You” pays hommage to Ibeyi’s father, Cuban percussionist Anga Díaz, who died in 2006, and to their friend Parisian beatmaker Kid Atlaas, who passed away in 2014.

The song features samples from both of them: “Round Midnight” by Angá Diaz and “Winter Is Coming” by Kid Atlaas.
